Linear model selection and model regularization

.

$$ Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p + \epsilon $$

, interpretablity , predictive performance .

.

Why consider alternatives?

  • Prediction accuracy : $p > n$ , least square estimation . .

  • Model interpretability : feature . feature selection variable selection .

  • Subset selection : $p$ predictor .

  • Shrinkage (regularization) : $p$ predictor , predictor 0 0 .

  • Dimension reduction : $p$ predictor $M$-dimensional subspace .

Subset selection

$p$ predictor , $k=1, 2, \cdots, p$ .

  • $k$ $\binom{p}{k}$ . .

    • $k$ . $\mathcal M_k$ .

    • predictor $\mathcal M_0$ .

  • $\mathcal M_0, \mathcal M_1, \cdots, \mathcal M_p$ best .

    • Best cross-validated prediction error, $C_p$ (AIC), BIC adjusted $R^2$ .

Shrinkage methods

constraint regularization 0 .

Ridge regression

Least square . $\beta$ .

$$ \mathrm{RSS} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( y_i - \beta - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{ij} \right)^2 $$

ridge regression $\beta$ .

$$ \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( y_i - \beta - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{ij} \right)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2 = \mathrm{RSS} + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2 $$

$\lambda \geq 0 $ tuning parameter .

$\hat \beta^{R}$ .

$\lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2$ shrinkage penalty , $\beta$ 0 .

$\lambda$ cross-validation .

$\lambda$ $\beta$ 0 .

x- $ \dfrac{|| \hat \beta_\lambda^R ||_2}{|| \hat \beta ||_2} $ .

$|| \cdot ||_2$ $\ell_2$-norm .

$$ || \beta ||_2 = \sqrt{\sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2} $$

, ridge regression predictor .

$$ \tilde x_{ij} = \frac{x_{ij}}{\sqrt{\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_{ij} - \bar x_j)^2}} $$

, . (feature) .

Bias-variance tradeoff

50 45 predictor . non-zero coefficient .

squared bias, variance, test error .

Lasso

Ridge regression $\lambda$ coefficient 0 0 $p$ predictor .

Lasso ridge , $\beta$ $\hat \beta_\lambda^L$ .

$$ \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( y_i - \beta - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{ij} \right)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} |\beta_j| = \mathrm{RSS} + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} |\beta_j| $$

, lasso $\ell_1$ penalty ridge $\ell_2$ penaltiy .

Ridge lasso coefficient 0 ridge $\lambda$ 0 .

lasso variable selection .

Lasso sparse .

$\lambda$ cross-validation .

Ridge Lasso

Lasso ridge regression .

$$ \arg \min_{\beta} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( y_i - \beta - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{ij} \right)^2 \text{ subject to } \sum_{j=1} |\beta_j| \leq s $$

$$ \arg \min_{\beta} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( y_i - \beta - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{ij} \right)^2 \text{ subject to } \sum_{j=1} \beta_j^2 \leq s $$

, Ridge Lasso .

$\lambda$ cross-validation .

ridge regression cross-validation $\lambda$ .

lasso 10-fold cross-validation $\lambda$ .

(elastic net)

Ridge Lasso .

$$ \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( y_i - \beta - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{ij} \right)^2 + r \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} |\beta_j| + \frac{1-r}{2} \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2$$

$r$ .

with K-fold cross validation

k-fold cross validation .

In[19]:
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
import numpy as np
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

alphas = np.arange(0.01, 10, 0.01)

errs_alpha = [] # alpha 

for a in alphas:
    
    kfold_errs = []  #    
    
    kf = KFold(n_splits = 5, shuffle=True, random_state=1)
    
    for train_index, test_index in kf.split(X):
    
        X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
        y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
        
        std_scale = StandardScaler()
        std_scale.fit(X_train)
        
        X_train_std = std_scale.transform(X_train)
        X_test_std = std_scale.transform(X_test)
        
        ridge = Ridge(alpha = a)
        ridge.fit(X_train_std, y_train)
        
        kfold_errs.append(mean_squared_error(y_test, ridge.predict(X_test_std)))
        
    errs_alpha.append(np.mean(kfold_errs))
In[20]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

ax = plt.gca()
ax.plot(alphas, errs_alpha)
ax.set_xscale("log")
ax.plot(alphas[np.argmin(errs_alpha)], np.min(errs_alpha), marker = 'o')

plt.title("The ridge MSE as a function of the regularization parameter")
plt.axis("tight")
plt.show()

cross_val_score .

  • 'neg_mean_squared_error' MSE , mse .

  • cross_val_score , .

In[21]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, KFold
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge

# alpha 
alphas = np.arange(0.01, 10, 0.01)
errs_alpha = []
cv = KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

for a in alphas:
    
    # :  + Ridge 
    pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
        ('ridge', Ridge(alpha=a))
    ])
    
    neg_mse_scores = cross_val_score(pipeline, X, y, cv=cv, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
    
    #    MSE 
    errs_alpha.append(np.mean(-neg_mse_scores))


plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

ax = plt.gca()
ax.plot(alphas, errs_alpha)
ax.set_xscale("log")
ax.plot(alphas[np.argmin(errs_alpha)], np.min(errs_alpha), marker = 'o')

plt.title("The ridge MSE as a function of the regularization parameter")
plt.axis("tight")
plt.show()

With k-fold cross-validation

In[38]:
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
alphas = np.arange(0.1, 100, 0.1)

errs_alpha = [] # alpha 

cv = KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

for a in alphas:
    
    # :  + Ridge 
    pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
        ('ridge', Ridge(alpha=a))
    ])
    
    neg_mse_scores = cross_val_score(pipeline, X, y, cv=cv, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
    
    #    MSE 
    errs_alpha.append(np.mean(-neg_mse_scores))


plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

ax = plt.gca()
ax.plot(alphas, errs_alpha)
ax.set_xscale("log")
ax.plot(alphas[np.argmin(errs_alpha)], np.min(errs_alpha), marker = 'o')

plt.title("The ridge MSE as a function of the regularization parameter")
plt.axis("tight")
plt.show()
